# Instinct RPG — Teach the table

Player-facing assets exist to **get people playing**, not to replace the GM. Before adding or expanding
any mechanic in a primer, quick ref, or GM guide section aimed at **new players**, classify it:

| Class | Default | Examples |
|-------|---------|----------|
| **Pre-read** | Include in player primer | Deck/hand, basic checks, Hit Dice intro, card types at a glance, chargen steps, keyword one-liners |
| **Table-teach** | GM introduces when it happens | Contests, Threat pool procedure, Resolve setup, Snap Check full procedure, specialized check formats |

## Rules

1. **Table-teach mechanics** get at most: a name, a one-sentence pointer, and a glossary `<details>` or
   “your GM will walk you through this” callout. Do **not** write full procedures unless Annie
   explicitly promotes them to pre-read.
2. **Pre-read** content must match `design/core-rules.md` — never invent shortcuts that contradict
   doctrine.
3. When Annie chooses depth for a playtest (“teach-the-table” vs “full rules upfront”), **lock that
   scope** for the session and do not creep table-teach content into the main flow.
4. GM-facing guides may go deeper, but still distinguish “say at session start” vs “say when it
   first appears.”

